Sound shift from ''saburai'' (see below), itself the {{m|ja|連用形|tr=ren'yōkei|pos=stem or continuative form}} of classical verb {{m|ja|侍ふ|tr=saburafu||to [[serve]]|pos=modern ''saburau''}}, ultimately derived from {{m|ja|さ|tr=sa-||pos=prefix meaning "[[early]]"}} + {{m|ja|守らふ|tr=morafu||to [[keep watch]]|pos=modern ''morau''}}.

The shift from ''saburaf-'' → ''samuraf-'' is due to the development of the {{m|ja|女性語|tr=josei-go||{{w|Gender differences in spoken Japanese|women's language}}}} in {{w|Middle Japanese}}, expected from {{m|ja|候|tr=sōrō||[[service]]|pos=classical ''saurafu''}}.

